<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the ideal C:N ratio for compost?", answer: "The ideal carbon-to-nitrogen (C:N) ratio for a hot, fast-finishing compost pile is 25:1 to 30:1. Below 20:1 the pile is nitrogen-rich: it heats up fast, then smells like ammonia and loses nitrogen as gas. Above 40:1 the pile is carbon-rich: it decomposes slowly, doesn't heat up, and can tie up nitrogen in the soil if you use it before it finishes. The calculator tells you which side of ideal you are on and how to adjust." },
  { question: "What are browns and greens?", answer: "Browns are carbon-rich, dry, brown materials: dry leaves, straw, cardboard, newsprint, wood chips, sawdust, and eggshells. Greens are nitrogen-rich, wet, fresh materials: grass clippings, kitchen scraps, coffee grounds, manure, and green plant trimmings. The names have nothing to do with color — coffee grounds are brown but classify as green, and dry coffee filters are brown in both color and category." },
  { question: "What ratio of browns to greens by volume?", answer: "By volume, a good rule is 2 to 3 parts browns to 1 part greens, because browns are lighter and fluffier than greens for the same weight. By weight, roughly 1:1 to 2:1 browns to greens gets you close to 30:1 C:N. The calculator works in weight because that is more precise. For most home composters, a loose 2:1 by volume is close enough without weighing." },
  { question: "How do I know if my compost pile is the right ratio?", answer: "Smell and temperature tell you. A pile that is 25:1 to 30:1 heats to 130-160°F within a few days, smells earthy, and shrinks visibly as it decomposes. A pile that smells like ammonia is too nitrogen-rich — add more browns. A pile that sits cold and does not shrink is too carbon-rich — add more greens and water. A pile that smells sour or swampy is too wet and compacted, regardless of ratio." },
  { question: "Does the C:N ratio need to be exact?", answer: "No — compost is forgiving. Anything from 20:1 to 40:1 will eventually produce finished compost; the ratio just changes how fast and how hot it runs. Hot composting (fast, kills weed seeds and pathogens, finishes in 4 to 8 weeks) needs 25:1 to 30:1. Cold composting (passive, takes 6 to 12 months) works at any reasonable ratio. Match your effort level to the method you want to use." }
]) %>

